<p>
I've spent the last 12 years managing paid social budgets, most recently as Social Media Marketing Director at
National Debt Relief, where I ran Meta and TikTok spend at over $1M a month in a regulated industry with legal
and compliance sitting in on campaign reviews. I built out Meta's Conversions API integration there, ran
holdout-market incrementality tests, and lived through the platform's shift from an audience-targeting tool to
something closer to a creative-scoring engine. That's the lens this piece comes from: not an outside observer,
someone who has had to defend a media plan to a CFO when the dashboard said one thing and the following week's
delivery said another.
</p>

<p>
Common Thread Collective published a framework in June 2026 called the CTC Canon, and their VP of Paid Media
Tony Chopp walked through the Meta-specific piece of it on the eCommerce Playbook podcast. It's a genuinely
useful codification of how account management has changed. I wanted to check it against people with no
methodology to sell: Meta's own engineering blog, and independent practitioners like Jon Loomer and Andrew
Foxwell who've been doing this as long or longer than CTC has existed. Some of it holds up completely. Some of
it needs a caveat CTC didn't include.
</p>

<h2>The two systems most advertisers have never heard of</h2>

<p>
Meta's advertising engine now runs on two systems most people managing ad accounts couldn't name. The first is
Andromeda, a creative-first ad retrieval engine. The second is GEM, the Generative Evaluation Model, Meta's
ranking intelligence layer operating at LLM scale. Together they process billions of interactions daily and make
allocation decisions no human operator can replicate.
</p>

<p>
This isn't agency marketing copy. Meta's own engineering blog described Andromeda in December 2024 as a
personalized ads retrieval engine that scales to a large volume of ad creatives using an efficient hierarchical
index. The headline number: a 10,000x increase in the complexity of the models used for ad retrieval, the step
that narrows a pool of tens of millions of ads down to a few thousand candidates, plus a 10x gain in inference
efficiency. Third-party coverage consistently cites a roughly 6% recall and 8% ad quality improvement from the
rollout.
</p>

<p>
GEM sits downstream as the ranking layer. Meta formally unveiled it in a November 2025 engineering paper,
and trade coverage describes it as the largest foundation model Meta has built for a recommendation system,
trained at roughly GPT-4 scale across thousands of GPUs. It had quietly started shipping on Reels months before
that paper came out.
</p>

<p>
The practical upshot: Meta is no longer an audience-first platform. It's creative-first. Your targeting
selections matter far less than the creative you put into the system. The algorithm finds the audience. Your
job is to give it signal.
</p>

<p>
Jon Loomer, who has covered Meta ads independently for a decade with no agency or software to sell, backs this
read using Meta's own language: the rise of AI-enabled ad tools has shifted the winning lever from niche
targeting to creative diversification. But he adds a check worth keeping in mind before crediting or blaming the
algorithm for anything: Andromeda "should improve performance overall, but it won't guarantee results," and poor
performance is more often a creative or offer problem than a platform problem.
</p>

<h2>The breakdown effect: why yesterday's ROAS lies to you</h2>

<p>
One of the more counterintuitive ideas in the CTC Canon is what Chopp calls the breakdown effect: historical
ROAS does not predict future ROAS. Meta says this outright in its own documentation, that the relationship
between historical performance and future delivery is not deterministic.
</p>

<p>
I'd put it plainer. If you're making decisions off yesterday's ROAS by ad, you're working from a small,
backward-looking sample to predict a future the system already models with far more signal than your dashboard
shows you. I've watched an ad get killed for a bad three-day stretch that would have recovered by day seven, and
I've watched the reverse. The instinct to intervene daily is exactly the instinct that needs to go.
</p>

<h2>How CTC structures an account</h2>

<p>
The Canon uses a deliberately simple three-tier hierarchy. At the campaign level: sales objective, value
optimization, minimum ROAS, ASC or CBO to let Meta handle budget allocation, with an inflated budget and cost
controls. At the ad set level: a seven-day click optimization window, broad targeting, acquisition and retention
exclusions, with ROAS targets living here rather than at the campaign level. At the ad level: AI enhancements
wherever a brand is willing to test, including dynamic creative and multiple URL testing.
</p>

<p>
Two campaign types run underneath that structure. Evergreen campaigns run continuously, split between
acquisition and retention, with ad sets filling sequentially with new creative up to Meta's current 150-ad limit,
plus a dedicated DABA ad set inside acquisition. Marketing moment campaigns are time-bound, tied to sales,
launches, or any event with a defined start and end date.
</p>

<h2>Budget liquidity: the variance is the point</h2>

<p>
One of the most misunderstood ideas in Meta advertising is budget liquidity. CTC deliberately runs inflated
budgets with cost controls, not despite the day-to-day spend variance this creates, but because of it. Meta
calls this liquidity: the system's ability to spend aggressively during cheap inventory moments and pull back
during expensive ones. Setting an inflated budget and enforcing profitability through a minimum ROAS or cost cap
lets the algorithm move freely across the time spectrum. That variance is the system working correctly, not a
sign something's broken.
</p>

<h2>Where the creative-volume consensus holds, and where it doesn't</h2>

<p>
This is genuinely the mainstream position now, not just a CTC opinion. Andrew Foxwell, whose Foxwell Founders
network spans roughly 550 agencies and brands managing over $500 million a month in Meta spend, independently
arrived at the same creative-diversification-first conclusion. His 2026 material is built around net-new
concepts and messaging rather than funnel mechanics.
</p>

<p>
But his own Foxwell x Motion 2026 State of Agencies report found that only 11% of agencies have a clear
top-performing AI-generated ad, despite widespread AI creative adoption. That complicates the popular shorthand
of "just generate more AI variants." Volume without real conceptual diversity doesn't work, and there's a
specific technical reason why: Andromeda clusters visually and semantically similar ads into a single retrieval
"ticket." Ten ads with the same product shot and different headlines count as one shot on goal, not ten. That's
the actual mechanism behind "big swings, not minor variations," not a stylistic preference CTC invented.
</p>

<p>
It cuts the other way too. Andromeda's similarity detection can suppress an entire cluster if it judges the
core concept weak, which is why a winning ad sometimes dies off with no warning: the algorithm judged the whole
cluster fatigued, not any single creative in it. CTC's own framing (creative strategy as a volume mechanism, not
an efficiency mechanism) accounts for this, but a lot of the "just make more ads" advice circulating in the
industry doesn't carry that nuance, and it risks diluting signal on the budget-per-creative math smaller
advertisers tend to ignore.
</p>

<h2>Never turn off an ad</h2>

<p>
This is the single most common mistake CTC sees brands make, and it runs against a decade of media buying habit.
When you turn off an ad with poor historical ROAS, you're solving a problem the system has already solved. If
you're running a CBO with cost controls, the algorithm has already reduced allocation to that ad based on
signals you can't see. Turning it off doesn't improve outcomes. It removes optionality from the machine.
</p>

<p>
Foxwell lands in similar territory from a different angle: his public position is to put close to 100% of
budget on cost controls, mostly bid caps, and let Meta's system suppress the likely losers instead of a human
pulling the trigger early. Structurally that's the same logic as never touching an ad manually. But it's not
unanimous. Cody Plofker at Jones Road Beauty prefers bid caps over cost caps specifically for tighter control,
and there's a live practitioner debate about reading learning-phase signals in layers, click-through and hook
rate first, funnel signals second, rather than adopting a blanket never-touch rule at every budget tier.
</p>

<h2>Signal quality: the part nobody disputes</h2>

<p>
Before any of the above matters, the algorithm needs clean data. The components: CAPI integration sending
server-side events directly from your backend to Meta, bypassing ad blockers and incomplete pixel fires. An
Event Match Quality score of 7 out of 10 or higher, since below that threshold you're optimizing against
degraded data. Purchase signal integrity audited monthly, because if Meta is only receiving 80% of your actual
purchase events, it's optimizing on incomplete data and both performance and measurement suffer. Clean audience
definitions for acquisition, retention, and existing customers, configured at the account level.
</p>

<p>
This part is closer to settled infrastructure than debated philosophy. Every serious named source agrees on it.
Where it gets more interesting is that Meta's April 2026 one-click CAPI rollout has made baseline EMQ hygiene
nearly free for everyone, including advertisers who couldn't previously justify the engineering lift. That
undercuts any framing of clean data as a durable competitive moat. It's becoming table stakes, fast.
</p>

<h2>Solving underspend: a four-phase sequence</h2>

<p>
When delivery falls short, CTC works through a defined sequence in order, before touching anything else.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Phase 1: Creative expansion.</strong> Deploy additional creative into evergreen and active marketing
moment campaigns, prioritizing genuine diversity of concept over minor variations. This is almost always the
right first move.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Phase 2: Bid surface expansion.</strong> Duplicate evergreen campaigns into lowest cost, bid cap, or cost
cap bidding using the same creative pool. A different bidding mechanism accesses a different audience without
any additional segmentation.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Phase 3: Underspend ad recovery.</strong> Launch a dedicated ASC campaign, single ad set, value
optimized, same ROAS target as evergreen, populated with ads from evergreen where spend is under 3x the CPA
target. These are ads that never got a fair opportunity to scale.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Phase 4: Constraint relaxation.</strong> Expand beyond current efficiency limits only when business
performance justifies it, meaning adjusting the ROAS target or cost cap itself. Last lever, not first.
</p>

<h2>What this means if you're running the account</h2>

<p>
Three jobs, and I'd say this matches what actually worked in the accounts I ran. Ensure correct budget
allocation with no artificial limitations at the campaign level. Ensure the bid matches the business objective,
meaning the ROAS target or cost cap reflects real unit economics, not a number that felt safe in a planning
meeting. Identify and launch new creative, continuously. Feed the machine. That's most of the job now, and it's
a genuinely different job than the one media buyers were trained to do five years ago.
</p>

<p>
If your account still looks like a 2021 structure, fragmented campaigns, ad-level kill decisions made off a
three-day dashboard, thin creative volume, that's usually not a targeting problem. It's a structure problem.
</p>

<hr />

